Message from Nadia MAGNENAT THALMANN
University of Geneva
------------------------------------


The seventh Computer Animation Conference being held in Geneva 
will take place this year in conjonction with DIGIMEDIA.

DIGIMEDIA is a new conference that will bring together researchers, 
users of multimedia technology, people of television and communication 
agencies, and producers of TV series and programs.

Our participants to the Computer Animation conference will have the 
opportunity to also attend all conferences and panels offered in the
DIGIMEDIA program.

What you will see at the DIGIMEDIA conference are two kinds of programs: 
what is available today for commecial production, and what will be 
available in the future.

What is available today commercially is what researchers have shown 
more than 10 years ago. Everyone remembers the wonderful films 
"The Juggler" (1982) from Triple I, and "Sexy Robot" (1985) from 
Robert Abel. Already at this time, production houses were recording 
real data from a real person and cloning it on a virtual one.

To make special effects in films and show the appearance of virtual 
humans, these techniques are still interesting today due to real-time 
recording. But these virtual humans are unable to play any role by 
themselves. What researchers try to do is recreate autonomous life 
by giving the computer all the know-how, or appropriate physical 
and behavioral models. In this case, we, as real humans, will be able 
to speak to virtual actors. With them, we will be able to interact 
and exchange information. They will learn from us as we will learn 
from them. 

The virtual human will no longer be considered to be just a picture, 
a stupid clone that repeats what a real actor has made alone. He will 
virtualy exist by itself. Like a virtual new born, through years, it
will grow in autonomy, in consciousness, in behavior.

This is the research's challenge for the coming years. The top 
researchers from all over the world will be present at Computer 
Animation '94 and will have the pleasure to discuss these new 
topics and show you the results.

Do not miss it, come and see the latest breakthroughs ...


