Invited speakers
----------------

Norman I. BADLER is the Cecilia Fitler Moore Professor and Chair 
of Computer and Information Science at the University of Pennsylvania 
and has been on that faculty since 1974. Active in computer graphics 
since 1968 with more than 80 technical papers, his research focuses 
on human figure modeling, manipulation, and animation. Badler received 
the BA degree in Creative Studies Mathematics from the University of
California at Santa Barbara in 1970, the MSc in Mathematics in 1971,
and the Ph.D. in Computer Science in 1975, both from the University 
of Toronto. He is Co-Editor of the Journal of Graphical Models and 
Image Processing. He also directs the Computer Graphics Research 
Facility with two full time staff members and about 40 students.


David BARAFF has been an Assistant Professor in Carnegie-Mellon 
University's Robotics Institute, and School of Computer Science, since 
1992. He received his Ph.D. from Cornell University in 1992, where 
he was a graduate student in Cornell's Program of Computer Graphics 
and Department of Computer Science. He received his Bs.E. in Computer 
Science from the University of Pennsylvania in 1987. At Cornell, he 
was named an AT&T Bell Laboratories Ph.D. Fellow in 1988. Dr. Baraff's 
research interests lie in realistic physical modeling of contacting 
and colliding objects for computer graphics and robotics applications.


Paul BOURGINE is a graduate from the Ecole Polytechnique of Paris. 
After his Ph.D. in Mathematical Economy he becomes senior researcher 
in Computer Science. He is the head of the Artificial Life and 
Artificial Intelligence Lab. of the CEMAGREF, the french institute 
of agricultural and environmental engineering research. He has 
co-organized the 2nd international conference on economics and 
artificial intelligence (CECOIA2, 1990) and the first european 
conference on artificial life (ECAL, 1991). He is a co-editor of 
"Economics and Cognitive Science" (Pergamon Press) and "Towards a 
practice of autonomous system" (MIT Press).


Tom CALVERT is a Professor of Computing Science, Engineering Science 
and Kinesiology and Director of the Centre for Systems Science at 
Simon Fraser University. He has degrees in electrical engineering 
from University College London (B.Sc.), Wayne State University (MSEE) 
and Carnegie-Mellon University (Ph.D.). He is former VP Research and 
Information Systems at SFU (1985-1990) and President of the Science 
Council of BC (1990-1992). Before joining SFU in 1972, he was on the 
faculty at Carnegie-Mellon University. He is a member of IEEE, ACM 
and the Association of Professional Engineers and Geoscientists of BC.


Hermann MAURER, Ph.D. in Mathematics from the University of Vienna 
in 1965, is Professor at Graz University of Technology, Director of 
the Institute for Hypermedia in Graz, Honorary Doctorate from the 
Polytechnical University of Sankt-Petersburg, Foundation Director of 
the Hypermedia Unit of the University of Auckland, Chief Advisor for 
Multimedia for the Museum of New-Zealand. He is also adjunct Professor 
at the University of Auckland. He is author of some 400 publications, 
including 10 books. He is also project leader of a number of 
multi-million dollar projects. His main current areas of interest 
are multimedia and networked versions thereof and applications of 
such systems for electronics publishing, education, general 
information systems and museum guidance and exhibit systems.


Nelson MAX is a Professor at the University of California, Davis 
Livermore, and a computer scientist at Lawrence Livermore Laboratory 
since 1977. His research interests are realism in images of nature,
molecular graphics, computer animation, and 3D scientific visualization. 
He has served as computer graphics director for two dome-screen 
stereo movies for the Fujitsu pavilions at Expo '85 and Expo '90 
in Japan. He received a B.S. in mathematics from John Hopkins 
University in 1963, and a Ph.D. in mathematics from Harvard 
University in 1967.


Jean-Arcady MEYER, born in 1941, is an engineer of the Ecole Nationale 
Superieure de Chimie de Paris and in Human Psychology, graduate in 
Animal Psychology, and holds a Ph.D. in Biology. He is currently 
Research Director at the CNRS and works in the Bio-Informatics Group 
of the Ecole Normale Superieure. His main scientific interests are 
the interactions of learning, development and evolution in adaptive 
systems, both natural and artificial. Together with S.W. Wilson, 
Dr. Meyer initiated the SAB (Simulation of Adaptive Behavior: from 
animals to animats) series of international conferences. He is the 
Editor-in-Chief of the journal Adaptive Behavior.


Jean-Pierre MULLER is professor of Computer Science at the University 
of Neuchatel, since 1990. He received his Ph.D. of Philosophy from 
the National Institute of Technology of Grenoble in 1987. His 
research interest lies in robotics applications and Artificial 
Intelligence. Dr Muller is member of the Executive committee 
of the Swiss Group for Artificial Intelligence and Cognitive 
Science and of the European Coordinating Committee for Artificial 
Intelligence.


Alex Paul PENTLAND received his Ph.D. from the Massachusetts 
Institute of Technology in 1982, and from there went to teach at 
Stanford University and work at the SRI (Stanford Research Institute) 
AI Center. He is currently Head of Perceptual Computing Section at 
the Media Laboratory, a group that includes over fifty researchers 
in computer vision, graphics, speech, music, and human-machine 
interaction. He has published more than 160 scientific articles 
in computer vision, graphics, and human vision, and has won 
international awards from both the American Association for 
Articifial Intelligence(AAAI) and the Institute of Electrical 
and Electronics Engineers.


